The wife of the Commissioner of Police in Edo State, Mrs. Jummai Abutu has appealed to corporate organisations to partner with the police with a view to providing capacity building programme and empowerment scheme for the officers. This, she said, will improve the wellbeing of families of officers whose service were prematurely truncated while in active duty. Mrs Abutu spoke in Benin city when she led members of the Police Officers’ Wives Association (POWA) on a visit to Chief Executive Officer of Zico oil Chief Isaac Ikekhuame in Benin city. She said the officers’ wives were seeking synergy in the areas of building a skill acquisition centre to assist in empowering dependants of slain officers to cushion the effect of the loss of their bread winners   ‘Ekiti, Osun polls litmus test for 2023…     826 Plateau pilgrims set for Saudi Arabia     MSSN holds Ummahaat conference   “In view of the challenges faced by police officers and their spouses in areas of personnel, funding, equipment, antiquated penal codes, public relations, welfare, shortage of quality personnel and compensation whenever police men and officers are either injured or die in active service, hence the need for the synergy between POWA and your organization,” she said. The advocacy visit by wives of the police officers, according to Mrs Abutu, was part of efforts to appreciate individuals and organisations who have contributed towards the welfare of police officers and their spouses She solicited for the support of Chief Ikekhuame in actualizing the dream which would benefit families of the officers. Chief Ikekhuame, who described the project as laudable, assured the visitor of his support in improving the welfare of officers and their families. He urged other spirited individuals and organisations to key into the initiative adding that POWA need them to carry on with these responsibilities thrust upon them  as a result of these challenges in active service